reviews.headline: I would purchase again
reviews.comments: I have the two lightest shades, Airplay and Debut. The lightest shade is very white on my eyelids and at first I hated it BUT then I learned how to use it, and I purchased the next debut.  You only need a little, I mean a little bit of this product or it will be cakey. I use my pinky finger and go into the pot and lightly swirl my finger to get the color and then I use a light pressing motion to place the product where I want it.  I use these to help keep my eye shadow on OR, Debut I can use alone to help even out my eyelids, add a little liner an mascara and be done.  I also use an eye primer and the combo helps to keep my eyeshadow from creasing. I also wait a couple of minutes before applying eyeshadow as the product can be tacky. I have hooded eyes and I'm 54.  My skin tone is light to light med with a tad of olive undertones.

reviews.headline: Drying
reviews.comments: I was hopeful this would be a good eyeshadow base, unfortunately it is very drying on the eyelids, not good for mature skin. If I don't put a good amount of moisturizer on my eyelids before applying, my eyelids look more textured, and they aren't even that wrinkly. So unfortunately, I don't recommend this product. Maybe it will work for you if you have very oily eyelids.

reviews.headline: Loving this eye shadow cream
reviews.comments: I tried this product at the store and found it a little bit dry and difficult to apply. But I figured out that if warmed up a little bit with the tip of the finger it turned more creamy. Now I am in love with it. I have the shades Airplay and Melody. Both work great when applied with my finger or brush. I would recommend to use a small amount at first and build up as you go. They are super waterproof and stay put all day. Now I want a dark color to use a liner.

It starts out very creamy and smooth but starts drying before I can get it blended over my lid and it dries so thick it looks terrible with eyeshadow on top. It is thick and grips the shadow so much I couldn't blend it. Not for me.

reviews.headline: Makes A Big Difference
reviews.comments: I was using a couple different drugstore eye primers, but was still having trouble with my slightly hooded eyes eating my eyeshadow. By mid-morning, my look would be gone. I thought I was going to have to try something pricey, and was going to get MAC Painterly next. But, saw this, which looked so similar. This works! I have mature eyes, too. I apply the primer and some powder. My shadow is locked on all day. It doesn't crease or fall. This is my new go-to.

faceoff_positive.comments:
I have received the Morphe Solo Artist Priming Cream Eyeshadow in the shade Remix for free in exchange for my review. 

Remix is a cool toned dark brown shade. My understanding is that this can be a two in one, a primer or used as a cream eyeshadow or both depending on the look you are trying to create.

It is easy to apply with a finger. It does stain your finger a bit. The pigmentation is about a 3.7/5 for me. It's build-able. As you apply with your finger though and blend, it can sheer out. Which could be a good thing for some but it is more work to layer. I need to do about 2-3 layering to get the intensity I am looking for (intense, not sneered). 

If you want to use this as a cream shadow, do your transition/crease shades first because it is little patchy. No fault of the product, skin moves and it just is harder to blend. It could get a little muddy if you start first with the pot and then using powdered shadows unless you strictly just do your eyelid and avoid patting whatever is left to the crease. 

As a cream eyeshadow, it is okay, but for a primer, it is more ideal and good for doing darker looks, laying this as your base and patting black eyeshadow if you want a dark eye look. 

I have tried the primer/cream shadow with powder eyeshadow and used as a stand alone with liquid glitter shadow as a topper. I prefer using this as a stand alone and adding some glitter for pizzaz. I avoided mascara in this look to show the product more clearly. 

As a cream eyeshadow, the staying power is average. I get about 8 hours of wear. It does fade a little bit, at least on me. 

I would be more interested in lighter colours, just for the ease of blending but I do see the vision and concept of where morphe is going with this. This is a decent base if you need a dark base for your black eyeshadows or liquid shadows, black based chrome shadows etc. 

All in all, I'm not too sure if I'd purchase more darker colours. I need to play around with incorporating other eyeshadows more. I do mostly rely on my fingers as I find it easiest to apply. I do think the colour is nice as a stand alone. Id recommend this if you're wanting to try a cool toned dark brown 2 in 1 cream eyeshadow / primer.
faceoff_positive.headline: Easy to use and flattering

faceoff_negative.comments:
I was drawn to the Solo Artist Priming Cream Eyeshadow in 'Mixtape' due to its dual-purpose claim as both a primer and a standalone eyeshadow. The shade "Mixtape" is indeed a lovely neutral, offering a versatile hue suitable for various looks. However, I encountered some issues with its performance.

The texture is creamy and applies smoothly, but I found that it didn't set as firmly as I'd hoped. On my oily eyelids, it began to crease and fade after just a few hours, even when used with a setting powder. This was disappointing, especially since it's marketed as a long-wearing product.

While it might work better for those with drier skin or when layered under powder shadows, it didn't meet my expectations for all-day wear. I appreciate the concept, but the execution left something to be desired.
faceoff_negative.headline: Beautiful Shade, But Performance Falls Short
